{
  "doc_id": "2180",
  "text": "Dysfunctional neurotransmitter trafficking is another known problem in schizophrenia, though its root cause has yet to be elucidated. Both reelin and Shank family member proteins are involved in trafficking of neurotransmitters [CITATION_1] and synaptic scaffolding and integrity [CITATION_2] , but they are likely not the only factors affecting neurotransmitters like GABA, glutamate, and dopamine. GABA dysfunction is implicated in ASD as well as schizophrenia and is thought to be responsible for inhibitory transmission and social deficits in ASD [CITATION_3] as well as verbal working memory and flat affect [CITATION_4] in schizophrenia. Reduced GABAA receptor [CITATION_5] and related protein [119••] expression has been found in the cortex of individuals with schizophrenia. One study shows that disrupting proper GABAAa2 clustering in frontal cortex in mice induces working memory and PPI deficits [CITATION_6] , which mimics human pathophysiology and symptomatology.",
